{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-casual-guide-to-dirac-notation-17961670ae7a", "time": 1683009736.261321, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-casual-guide-to-dirac-notation-17961670ae7a/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "A Casual Guide to Dirac Notation. Understanding common notation in\u2026 | by Gojo Satoru | Towards Data Science", "h1": "A Casual Guide to Dirac Notation", "description": "The notion of quantum mechanics has been around for almost one hundred years. In spite of this, it remains a very difficult subject to learn and comprehend due to competing theories and probabilistic\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["\u201cIf you are not completely confused by quantum mechanics, you do not understand it.\u201d \u2014 Niels Bohr", "The notion of quantum mechanics has been around for almost one hundred years. In spite of this, it remains a very difficult subject to learn and comprehend due to competing theories and probabilistic nature(as illustrated by Bohr\u2019s quote). However difficult to grasp, there still remain profound theories that are the backbone of modern quantum mechanics. One of the more interesting applications of quantum mechanics, specifically for my own research, is in the realm of quantum computing. This is by no means an article explaining superposition, entanglement, or the potential for parallel worlds. Nevertheless, I want to introduce common notation used when discussing these topics \u2014 when you read about them, you will have a general understanding of the systems they are describing.", "Let\u2019s take a look at a traditional vector in a 3-dimensional space\u2026", "Basis vectors in 3-dimensional space are defined as\u2026", "More generally, basis vectors, regardless of dimensionality, are denoted as\u2026", "This means any vector can be decomposed into a linear combination of basis vectors\u2026", "Similarly using Dirac notation, a ket can be used to denote a vector\u2026", "Basis vectors can also be written as kets\u2026", "This means we can decompose our original vector into a linear combination of basis vectors using kets\u2026", "Let\u2019s consider the same vector in 3-dimensional space\u2026", "Transposing and taking the complex conjugate yields\u2026", "Transposing turns the column vector into a row vector, and in this case, the complex conjugate just yields our original values (as we are assuming they\u2019re real). This is called the Hermitian conjugate and is denoted with a dagger.", "Using Dirac notation this can be written as a bra vector\u2026", "Bras and kets can also be written together to signify an inner product. This inner product is a generalization of the dot product. Considering the original vector in 3-dimensional space\u2026", "If we want to denote the dot product using Dirac notation between this vector and its Hermitian product we can combine our bra and ket as\u2026", "Quantum mechanics is as interesting as it is complex. The importance of this field cannot be understated, especially with quantum computers right around the corner. Understanding common notation in these fields of study is the first step in developing (some) understanding of elementary theories. If you\u2019re interested in learning more about quantum mechanics I would recommend this book:", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F17961670ae7a&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-casual-guide-to-dirac-notation-17961670ae7a&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect